  "local_port": 37732,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I make homemade pancakes without baking soda?",
  "response": "If you want to make homemade pancakes without using baking soda, you can still achieve fluffy pancakes by using baking powder. Baking powder is a complete leavening agent on its own, which means it contains both an acid and a base. Here\u2019s a simple recipe:\n\n### Ingredients:\n- 1 cup all-purpose flour\n- 2 tablespoons granulated sugar\n- 1 tablespoon baking powder\n- 1/4 teaspoon salt\n- 1 cup milk\n- 1 large egg\n- 2 tablespoons melted butter or vegetable oil\n- 1 teaspoon vanilla extract (optional)\n\n### Instructions:\n\n1. **Mix Dry Ingredients:**\n   - In a large bowl, whisk together the flour, sugar, baking powder, and salt until well combined.\n\n2. **Combine Wet Ingredients:**\n   - In a separate bowl, beat the egg, then add the milk, melted butter or oil, and vanilla extract. Stir until mixed thoroughly.\n\n3. **Combine Wet and Dry Ingredients:**\n   - Pour the wet ingredients into the dry ingredients. Stir gently until just combined. Be careful not to overmix; a few lumps are perfectly fine.\n\n4. **Cook the Pancakes:**\n   - Preheat a non-stick skillet or griddle over medium heat. Lightly grease with cooking spray or a small amount of butter.\n   - Pour about 1/4 cup of batter onto the skillet for each pancake. Cook until bubbles begin to form on the surface and the edges look set, about 2-3 minutes.\n   - Flip the pancakes and cook for another 1-2 minutes on the other side, until golden brown and cooked through.\n\n5. **Serve:**\n   - Serve the pancakes warm with your favorite toppings, such as maple syrup, fresh fruit, or whipped cream.\n\n### Tips:\n- If you want extra fluffy pancakes, let the batter rest for about 5-10 minutes before cooking to allow the baking powder time to react.\n- Ensure your skillet or griddle is at the right temperature; too hot and the pancakes will burn on the outside while remaining uncooked inside.\n- You can also add mix-ins like chocolate chips or blueberries to the batter right before cooking for added flavor.\n\nEnjoy your homemade pancakes!",
